  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. Here are some key details:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering\n\n2. Specific Sentencing Factors:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Complexity of the scheme\n- Whether it involved organized criminal activity\n- Prior criminal history of the defendant\n\n3. Specific Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal offenses\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 addresses monetary transactions\n\n4. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Potential asset seizure\n\nIt's important to note that actual sentencing can vary based on specific circumstances and judicial discretion. Anyone facing such charges should consult a qualified criminal defense attorney for precise legal guidance.",
